sistence in academic criticism. Anderson shows that character-criticism illuminates both the moral life of characters, and our understanding of literary form. In offering new perspectives on the question of fictional character, this thought-provoking book makes an important intervention in literary studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelski, Rita, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFelski, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoi, Toril, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMoi, Toril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226658834423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226658834.jpg  a978-3-11-071194-3  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles